sted behavior of key actors? The collaborative effort of a group of distinguished scholars, this volume breaks new ground in demonstrating how ideas can shape policy, even when actors are motivated by rational self-interest.After an introduction outlining a new framework for approaching the role of ideas in foreign policy making, well-crafted case studies test the approach. The function of ideas as "road maps" that reduce uncertainty is examined in chapters on human rights, decolonialization, the creation of socialist economies in China and Eastern Europe, and the postwar Anglo-American economic settlement. Discussions of parliamentary ideas in seventeenth-century England and of the Single European Act illustrate the role of ideas in resolving problems of coordination. The process by which ideas are institutionalized is further explored in chapters on the Peace of Westphalia and on German and Japanese efforts to cope with contemporary terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternational economic relationsxPhilosophy. 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aFerejohn, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrett, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalpern, Nina P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkenberry, G. John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://i